"Amano T., Smithers R.J., Sparks T.H., Sutherland W.J.","A 250-year index of first flowering dates and its response to temperature changes",2010,"Proceedings of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences","277","1693",,"2451","2457",,,10.1098/rspb.2010.0291,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77956493745&partnerID=40&md5=017ef55db3684f994ceafb592ae030d4","Biodiversity Division, National Institute for Agro-Environmental Sciences, 3-1-3, Kannondai, Tsukuba-shi, Ibaraki 305-8604, Japan; Conservation Science Group, Department of Zoology, University of Cambridge, Cambridge CB2 3EJ, United Kingdom; Woodland Trust, Autumn Park, Dysart Road, Grantham NG31 6LL, United Kingdom; Institute of Zoology, Poznań University of Life Sciences, Wojska Polskiego 71C, 60-625 Poznań, Poland","Amano, T., Biodiversity Division, National Institute for Agro-Environmental Sciences, 3-1-3, Kannondai, Tsukuba-shi, Ibaraki 305-8604, Japan, Conservation Science Group, Department of Zoology, University of Cambridge, Cambridge CB2 3EJ, United Kingdom; Smithers, R.J., Woodland Trust, Autumn Park, Dysart Road, Grantham NG31 6LL, United Kingdom; Sparks, T.H., Institute of Zoology, Poznań University of Life Sciences, Wojska Polskiego 71C, 60-625 Poznań, Poland; Sutherland, W.J., Conservation Science Group, Department of Zoology, University of Cambridge, Cambridge CB2 3EJ, United Kingdom","Widespread concerns about global biodiversity loss have led to a growing demand for indices of biodiversity status. Today, climate change is among the most serious threats to global biodiversity. Although many studies have revealed phenological responses to climate change, no long-term community-level indices have been developed. We derived a 250-year index of first flowering dates for 405 plant species in the UK for assessing the impact of climate change on plant communities. The estimated community-level index in the most recent 25 years was 2.2-12.7 days earlier than any other consecutive 25-year period since 1760. The index was closely correlated with February-April mean Central England Temperature, with flowering 5.0 days earlier for every 1°C increase in temperature. The index was relatively sensitive to the number of species, not records per species, included in the model. Our results demonstrate how multi-species, multiple-site phenological events can be integrated to obtain indices showing trends for each species and across species. This index should play an important role in monitoring the impact of climate change on biodiversity. Furthermore, this approach can be extended to incorporate data from other taxa and countries for evaluating cross-taxa and cross-country phenological responses to climate change. © 2010 The Royal Society.","2010 target; First flowering; Global warming; Hierarchical model; Indicator; Phenology","biodiversity; climate change; diversity index; flowering; global warming; hierarchical system; phenology; temperature effect; biodiversity; climate change; conference paper; flower; growth, development and aging; history; plant; species difference; temperature; time; United Kingdom; Biodiversity; Climate Change; Flowers; Great Britain; History, 18th Century; History, 19th Century; History, 20th Century; Plants; Species Specificity; Temperature; Time Factors; United Kingdom",,,,,,"Balmford, A., Bennun, L., Ten Brink, B., Cooper, D., Cote, I.M., Crane, P., Dobson, A., Walther, B.A., The convention on biological diversity's 2010 target (2005) Science, 307 (5707), pp. 212-213. , DOI 10.1126/science.1106281; Both, C., Bouwhuis, S., Lessells, C.M., Visser, M.E., Climate change and population declines in a long-distance migratory bird (2006) Nature, 441, pp. 81-83. , doi:10.1038/nature04539; Chuine, I., Yiou, P., Viovy, N., Seguin, B., Daux, V., Ladurie, E.L., Historical phenology: Grape ripening as a past climate indicator (2004) Nature, 432, pp. 289-290. , doi:10. 1038/432289a; Cleland, E.E., Chuine, I., Menzel, A., Mooney, H.A., Schwartz, M.D.